Question 2:¶

You've already plot data from one stock. It is possible to plot multiples of them to support comparison.
To highlight different lines, customise line styles, markers, colors and include a legend to the plot.

In [63]:
fig, goog = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,8))
goog.plot(stocks.date,stocks.GOOG, label = "Google", linestyle='-')
goog.plot(stocks.date,stocks.AAPL, label = "Apple", linestyle='--')
goog.plot(stocks.date,stocks.AMZN, label = "Amazon", linestyle='-.')
goog.plot(stocks.date,stocks.FB, label = "Facebook", linestyle=':',dash_capstyle='round')
goog.plot(stocks.date,stocks.NFLX, label = "Netflix", linewidth=5, alpha=0.3)
goog.plot(stocks.date,stocks.MSFT, label = "Microsoft", linewidth=5, alpha=0.3, linestyle='--')
goog.set_title('Stocks')
goog.set_xlabel('Dates')
goog.set_ylabel('Stock prices')
goog.set_xticks([0,14,29,44,59,74,89,104])
goog.legend()
plt.xticks(rotation=0)
plt.show()

Question 3:¶

Some possible questions:

  • Are there differences between male and female when it comes to giving tips?
  • What attribute correlate the most with tip?

g.add_legend()
plt.show()
In [101]:
maledinner =  tips[(tips['sex']=='Male') & (tips['time']=='Dinner')]
femaledinner = tips[(tips['sex']=='Female') & (tips['time']=='Dinner')]
malelunch = tips[(tips['sex']=='Male') & (tips['time']=='Lunch')]
femalelunch = tips[(tips['sex']=='Female') & (tips['time']=='Lunch')]


fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=2, figsize=(15,9))
sns.histplot(maledinner,x='tip',kde = True, ax=ax[0])
sns.histplot(femaledinner,x='tip',kde = True, ax=ax[0],color = 'orange' )
sns.histplot(malelunch,x='tip',kde = True, ax=ax[1])
sns.histplot(femalelunch,x='tip',kde = True, ax=ax[1], color = 'orange')
plt.show()

The tips dataset¶

In [142]:
df = px.data.tips()
fig1 = px.scatter(
   df[(df['smoker']=='No')&(df['time']=='Dinner')], x="total_bill", y="tip", color="sex", 
   hover_data=df.columns, width=600, height=300, title = "no smoker at dinner")
fig2 = px.scatter(
   df[(df['smoker']=='No')&(df['time']=='Lunch')], x="total_bill", y="tip", color="sex", 
   hover_data=df.columns, width=600, height=300, title = "no smoker at lunch")
fig3 = px.scatter(
   df[(df['smoker']=='Yes')&(df['time']=='Dinner')], x="total_bill", y="tip", color="sex", 
   hover_data=df.columns, width=600, height=300, title = "smoker at dinner")
fig4 = px.scatter(
   df[(df['smoker']=='Yes')&(df['time']=='Lunch')], x="total_bill", y="tip", color="sex", 
   hover_data=df.columns, width=600, height=300, title = "smoker at lunch")
fig1.show()
fig2.show()
fig3.show()
fig4.show()
